eving Student Success (2010), this volume focuses on the best programs and practices in Canadian colleges and universities to improve the educational experiences of students who are Indigenous, people of colour, francophone, LGBTQQ, disabled, and adult learners, as well as international and first-generation students. Presenting findings obtained from both personal insight and relevant research, higher education practitioners and scholars from across the country detail the characteristics, concerns, and specific needs of each diverse group, to conclude that the success of these new students and the future of Canadian society depends on its post-secondary institutions’ capacities to acknowledge students’ differences, capitalize on their gifts, and accommodate them accordingly. Exploring the enriching breadth of university communities, Serving Diverse Students in Canadian Higher Education focuses on a new paradigm of individual differences and student success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)zCanada. 0aMinority college studentsxServices forzCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Inclusive Education.2bisacsh1 aBuckley, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Donna Hardy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelaney, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton-Hinch, Barb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHotchkiss, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoy, Chantal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeary, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewin, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIntyre, Susan, econtributo